│ "thoughts": "The user is encountering a `SIGABRT` due to an assertion failure in the       │
│ `loop-vectorize` pass. The assertion `PHINode should have one entry for each predecessor   │
│ of its parent basic block!` indicates that a PHI node in the transformed function has an   │
│ incorrect number of incoming values relative to its parent block's predecessors.\n\n### 1. │
│ Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `loop-vectorize` pass transforms a scalar loop into a       │
│ vectorized loop followed by a scalar remainder loop. This involves creating new basic      │
│ blocks and modifying the control flow graph. The issue arises because a PHI node outside   │
│ the loop is not correctly updated to reflect these changes. Specifically, the PHI node     │
│ `%use` in the `exit` block of the original function is not handled correctly during the    │
│ transformation.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log shows the crash occurs    │
│ after the `loop-vectorize` pass runs. The error message pinpoints the problematic PHI      │
│ node:\n```\nPHINode should have one entry for each predecessor of its parent basic         │
│ block!\n  %use = phi i64 [ %start2, %for.body ]\n```\nThis PHI node is in the `exit`       │
│ block. In the original IR, `exit` has only one predecessor, `%for.body`, so the PHI is     │
│ valid. The vectorization process alters the predecessors of the `exit` block. The          │
│ assertion failure implies that after this transformation, the PHI node was not updated to  │
│ match the new set of predecessors, leading to malformed IR.\n\n### 3. Root Cause           │
│ Analysis\n\nThe root cause lies in how the loop vectorizer handles values that are used    │
│ outside the loop but are defined within the loop's scope. The value `%start2` is defined   │
│ in the `entry` block, which is outside the loop. However, the PHI node `%use` in the       │
│ `exit` block takes `%start2` as an incoming value from the `%for.body` block.\n\nDuring    │
│ vectorization, the `loop-vectorize` pass creates a new exit block for the vectorized loop  │
│ (`vector.body.epil.iter.check` in this case). This new block becomes a predecessor to the  │
│ original `exit` block. The pass uses `LoopVectorizationLegality::AddLiveOut` to manage     │
│ values that are live-out of the loop. However, it fails to correctly handle the case of    │
│ the PHI node `%use`.\n\nThe function `LoopVectorizationLegality::AddLiveOut` is            │
│ responsible for identifying and preparing values that are used outside the loop. It should │
│ recognize that `%use` is a live-out value and ensure it's correctly computed after the     │
│ loop. The problem is that `AddLiveOut` does not properly trace the origin of the PHI's     │
│ operand `%start2` back to its definition outside the loop. It incorrectly assumes the      │
│ value is loop-variant because it's an operand of a PHI node in a successor block.\n\nThe   │
│ fix is to modify `LoopVectorizationLegality::AddLiveOut` to correctly handle this          │
│ scenario. When a PHI node in an exit block uses a value defined outside the loop,          │
│ `AddLiveOut` should recognize this and not create a reduction for it. Instead, it should   │
│ let the existing mechanisms for handling loop-invariant values take care of it. The        │
│ proposed edit achieves this by adding a check: if a PHI node's incoming value is defined   │
│ in a block that dominates the loop's preheader, it should be treated as a loop-invariant   │
│ value and not processed as a live-out that requires a reduction.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit   │
│ Point(s)\n\nThe following edit should be applied to                                        │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`:\n\n```cpp\n//                           │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:2201-2201\nif (isa<PHINode>(U) &&          │
│ L->isLoopExiting(U->getParent())) {\n  // A PHI in an exit block is not a reduction; it is │
│ either a live-out\n  // or should be ignored.\n  for (unsigned i = 0, e =                  │
│ U->getNumIncomingValues(); i != e; ++i) {\n    if (L->contains(U->getIncomingBlock(i)))    │
│ {\n      Value *V = U->getIncomingValue(i);\n      if (isa<Instruction>(V) &&              │
│ L->contains(cast<Instruction>(V)))\n        AddLiveOut(V);\n      else if (auto *PN =      │
│ dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {\n        if (L->contains(PN))\n          AddLiveOut(PN);\n         │
│ }\n    }\n  }\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nThis change ensures that when `AddLiveOut` encounters  │
│ a PHI node in a loop exit block, it correctly identifies whether the incoming values are   │
│ from within the loop. If an incoming value is from outside the loop (i.e., its defining    │
│ block is not contained in the loop), it is not added as a live-out, preventing the         │
│ creation of an unnecessary and incorrect reduction.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe bug is     │
│ caused by the `loop-vectorize` pass incorrectly identifying a loop-invariant value used in │
│ a PHI node in an exit block as a loop-variant live-out value. This leads to the creation   │
│ of a faulty reduction, which in turn results in malformed IR that fails verification. The  │
│ proposed fix corrects the logic in `LoopVectorizationLegality::AddLiveOut` to properly     │
│ distinguish between loop-variant and loop-invariant inputs to such PHI nodes, ensuring     │
│ that the transformed IR remains valid."})                                                  │
